james kariuki

Is CI/CD Becoming Outdated? The Shift to CI/PD Has Already Started
A lot of engineering teams still believe that once they implement CI/CD, they‚Äôve reached the ‚Äúmodern‚Äù software delivery standard. But the industry has moved forward, and there‚Äôs a major gap CI/CD no longer covers on its own.

The problem is simple: deploying to production is not the same as releasing value to users.

CI/CD: What Most Teams Do Today
You build, test, and deploy automatically.
 As soon as it hits production, every user gets the change.
The risk is obvious. If there‚Äôs a problem, all users feel it instantly. Rollbacks become stressful, customer impact is high, and outages spread fast.

CI/PD: Continuous Progressive Delivery
This is the evolution of CI/CD. The idea is to separate deploying code from releasing features.
Deploy code frequently, but release features carefully and in a controlled manner.
With CI/PD you can:
 ‚Ä¢ Roll out to a small percentage of users first
 ‚Ä¢ Target specific user groups, internal teams, or premium users
 ‚Ä¢ Use feature flags to enable or disable features without redeploying
 ‚Ä¢ Run A/B tests and validate value before full rollout
 ‚Ä¢ Reduce risk, gather data, and ship more confidently

This is why modern engineering teams are adopting progressive delivery. It‚Äôs becoming a standard for safer, data-driven, user-aware releases.
The Bottom Line
CI/CD helps you deploy fast.
 CI/PD helps you deploy fast, test safely, learn, and release intelligently.

I‚Äôm currently working on a CI/PD project using Argo Rollouts, Istio, and Prometheus to enable automated progressive delivery and intelligent rollbacks based on real-time metrics. The results are promising, and it‚Äôs clear this model is the future of high-quality software delivery.

If you haven‚Äôt started exploring CI/PD yet, now is the time. It‚Äôs not just about moving fast anymore  it‚Äôs about moving fast with control and confidence.




